Files:
- platform/mcp-server/src/plugin-management.ts (rewrite searchNpmPlugins)

Context:
The current searchNpmPlugins (line 188-241) spawns `npm search keywords:opentabs-plugin {query} --json` as a child process. This has two problems:
1. npm search defaults to 20 results — there are 104+ opentabs plugins, so most are invisible
2. npm search is slow (~630ms) because it spawns a Node.js process

The npm registry has a REST API at `GET /-/v1/search` that returns JSON directly:
- URL: `https://registry.npmjs.org/-/v1/search?text=keywords:opentabs-plugin&size=250`
- Returns: `{ objects: [{ package: { name, description, version, publisher, keywords, links } }], total: number }`
- `size` param: max 250 per page
- `from` param: offset for pagination
- Response time: ~170ms

The registry also supports direct package lookup:
- URL: `https://registry.npmjs.org/@opentabs-dev/opentabs-plugin-notion`
- Returns full package metadata (name, description, version, etc.) or 404
- This is how the CLI's `fetchPackageInfo` works (but via `npm view` CLI — we should use fetch() instead)

Changes:

1. Replace the `spawnAsync` + `npm search` approach with `fetch()` to the registry API. The function signature and return type (`PluginSearchResult[]`) stay the same.

2. For keyword search, fetch all opentabs plugins with pagination:
```typescript
const fetchAllPlugins = async (): Promise<NpmRegistrySearchResult[]> => {
  const results: NpmRegistrySearchResult[] = [];
  let from = 0;
  const size = 250;
  while (true) {
    const url = `https://registry.npmjs.org/-/v1/search?text=keywords:opentabs-plugin&size=${size}&from=${from}`;
    const resp = await fetch(url);
    if (!resp.ok) break;
    const data = await resp.json();
    results.push(...data.objects.map(o => o.package));
    if (results.length >= data.total) break;
    from += size;
  }
  return results;
};
```

The response shape for each object in `data.objects` is:
```
{ package: { name: string, description: string, version: string, publisher: { username: string }, keywords: string[], links: { npm: string } } }
```

3. For direct probe when a query is provided, check both scoped and unscoped names in parallel:
```typescript
const probeDirectPackage = async (query: string): Promise<NpmRegistrySearchResult | null> => {
  const candidates = [
    `@opentabs-dev/opentabs-plugin-${query}`,
    `opentabs-plugin-${query}`,
  ];
  for (const pkg of candidates) {
    const resp = await fetch(`https://registry.npmjs.org/${encodeURIComponent(pkg).replace('%40', '@')}`);
    if (resp.ok) {
      const data = await resp.json();
      const latest = data['dist-tags']?.latest;
      const versionData = latest ? data.versions?.[latest] : null;
      return {
        name: data.name,
        description: data.description ?? '',
        version: latest ?? '0.0.0',
        publisher: versionData?._npmUser?.name ?? 'unknown',
      };
    }
  }
  return null;
};
```

Note: the registry API URL for scoped packages uses the literal `@` (not encoded) and encodes `/` — e.g., `https://registry.npmjs.org/@opentabs-dev%2Fopentabs-plugin-notion`. However, `fetch()` handles this automatically if you pass the URL as-is: `https://registry.npmjs.org/@opentabs-dev/opentabs-plugin-notion`.

4. The rewritten searchNpmPlugins should:
   - Run the keyword search (fetchAllPlugins) and direct probe (if query) in parallel via Promise.all
   - Post-filter keyword results by query (same extractShortName logic as today)
   - Merge: direct probe result first, then filtered keyword results (deduped by name)
   - Map results to PluginSearchResult with displayName, same as today

5. Keep the existing timeout logic (NPM_SUBPROCESS_TIMEOUT_MS) but apply it to the fetch() calls instead of the child process. Use AbortController:
```typescript
const controller = new AbortController();
const timerId = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), NPM_SUBPROCESS_TIMEOUT_MS);
try {
  const resp = await fetch(url, { signal: controller.signal });
  ...
} finally {
  clearTimeout(timerId);
}
```

6. Remove the `spawnAsync` import if it's no longer used elsewhere in the file (check — it IS used by `runNpmGlobal` for install/uninstall, so keep it).

7. Remove the NpmSearchJsonEntry interface (no longer needed) — replace with a new interface for the registry API response shape.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the PluginSearchResult return type or the function signature
- Do NOT change how installPlugin/uninstallPlugin work — they still use npm CLI
- The registry URL must be `https://registry.npmjs.org` (the default npm registry)
- The function must still handle errors gracefully (network failures, malformed JSON)
- The timeout must still work and kill pending requests on timeout
- The direct probe candidates should match what the CLI does: `@opentabs-dev/opentabs-plugin-{query}` and `opentabs-plugin-{query}`
- If the query is already a fully qualified package name (starts with `@` or `opentabs-plugin-`), probe it directly as-is

Files:
- platform/cli/src/commands/plugin.ts (rewrite npmSearchPlugins and fetchPackageInfo)

Context:
The CLI has three relevant functions:
1. `npmSearchPlugins` (line 355-382): spawns `npm search keywords:opentabs-plugin {query} --json` — same 20-result limit as the server
2. `fetchPackageInfo` (line 279-310): spawns `npm view {pkg} name description version maintainers --json` — used for direct probes
3. `buildDirectLookupCandidates` (line 331-338): generates candidate package names for direct probes
4. `handlePluginSearch` (line 385-): orchestrates search + direct probe + merge + display

The CLI currently uses `spawnProcessSync` (synchronous child process spawning) for both npm search and npm view. Since Node.js 22+ has native `fetch()`, we can use it directly. However, the CLI's command handler is synchronous — `handlePluginSearch` is not async. This means we need to either:
- Make it async (preferred — the commander action handler supports async)
- Or use a synchronous HTTP approach

Recommendation: make `handlePluginSearch`, `npmSearchPlugins`, and `fetchPackageInfo` async, and update the commander action to `async (query) => { await handlePluginSearch(query); }`.

Changes:

1. Rewrite `npmSearchPlugins` to use fetch():
```typescript
const npmSearchPlugins = async (query?: string): Promise<NpmSearchPackage[]> => {
  const results: NpmSearchPackage[] = [];
  let from = 0;
  const size = 250;
  while (true) {
    const resp = await fetch(`https://registry.npmjs.org/-/v1/search?text=keywords:opentabs-plugin&size=${size}&from=${from}`);
    if (!resp.ok) break;
    const data = await resp.json();
    for (const obj of data.objects) {
      const pkg = obj.package;
      results.push({
        name: pkg.name,
        description: pkg.description,
        version: pkg.version,
        publisher: pkg.publisher?.username ? { username: pkg.publisher.username } : undefined,
      });
    }
    if (results.length >= data.total) break;
    from += size;
  }
  if (query) {
    const q = query.toLowerCase();
    return results.filter(
      r => extractShortName(r.name).toLowerCase().includes(q) || (r.description ?? '').toLowerCase().includes(q),
    );
  }
  return results;
};
```

2. Rewrite `fetchPackageInfo` to use fetch():
```typescript
const fetchPackageInfo = async (pkg: string): Promise<NpmSearchPackage | null> => {
  try {
    const resp = await fetch(`https://registry.npmjs.org/${pkg}`);
    if (!resp.ok) return null;
    const data = await resp.json();
    const latest = data['dist-tags']?.latest;
    if (!latest) return null;
    const versionData = data.versions?.[latest];
    return {
      name: data.name,
      description: data.description,
      version: latest,
      publisher: versionData?._npmUser?.name ? { username: versionData._npmUser.name } : undefined,
    };
  } catch {
    return null;
  }
};
```

3. Make `handlePluginSearch` async and update the commander action:
From: `.action((query?: string) => { handlePluginSearch(query); });`
To: `.action(async (query?: string) => { await handlePluginSearch(query); });`

4. Remove the NpmSearchJsonEntry interface (no longer needed).

5. The `spawnProcessSync` import may still be needed for other functions in the file (installPlugin, uninstallPlugin use `spawnProcessSync` via `runNpmGlobalSync`). Check before removing.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the NpmSearchPackage interface or how results are displayed
- Do NOT change installPlugin/uninstallPlugin — they still use npm CLI for actual package management
- The buildDirectLookupCandidates logic should remain the same — it correctly generates candidate names
- Error handling must be graceful — network failures should return empty results, not crash
- The KNOWN_OFFICIAL_PLUGIN_SLUGS constant can be removed if the direct probe + keyword search already covers all cases (the reason it existed was to find private packages that npm search excluded — with the full keyword search + direct probe, this is no longer needed)
